age"><img alt="" itemProp="image" data-src="https://d1b5h9psu9yexj.cloudfront.net/42400/Plantstraws_20230419-133230_full.jpeg" width="570" height="380" class="cf3feb4c c882c9ce" loading="lazy"/></div></a></div><div class="ce2bb787"><div><h3 class="b550f131 e26624a1 a1a87f29"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/42400/167766/4/173583?merchant=Plantstraws" class="dfb6b88d" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" title="Plantstraws" data-gtm-element="callout_product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Plantstraws" data-pick-type-id="7" data-pid="42400" data-store="Plantstraws" data-vars-store="Plantstraws" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/42400/167766/4/173583?merchant=Plantstraws" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_name" data-scp="callout_product" data-gtm-context="inline">Plantstraws</a></h3><h2 class="eafb159a"></h2></div><p class="ec57f3ca" data-scp="callout_description">Simple and ingenious, these brass tubes are threaded with a cotton cord to slowly draw water from the container vessel into the soil of your plants.</p><div class="dded66b7"><div data-scp="removed"><h4 class="efa3259d">Buying Options</h4><div class="b279b202 product-pricebox-0" data-source-id-order="0" data-country-code="US"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/42400/167766/4/173583?merchant=Plantstraws" class="b50e01ee" data-gtm-element="callout_buy_button_impression" data-link-type="button" data-merchant="Plantstraws" data-pick-type-id="7" data-pid="42400" data-store="Plantstraws" data-vars-store="Plantstraws" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/42400/167766/4/173583?merchant=Plantstraws" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-gtm-context="inline" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_button"><span>$27</span> from <span>Plantstraws</span></a></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The idea is simple and as old as time—a cotton cord draws water from one vessel to another—but the execution is a stroke of design genius. For plants that like moist soil, like baby’s tears <em>(Soleirolia soleirolii)</em> and umbrella papyrus<em> (Cyperus alternifolius)</em>, these Swedish <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/42400/167766/4/160316/?merchant=Plantstraws" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Plantstraws" data-pick-type-id="7" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/42400/167766/4/160316/?merchant=Plantstraws" data-vars-store="Plantstraws" data-gtm-context="chapter_a-beautiful-watering-system" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Plantstraws" data-pid="42400" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/42400/167766/4/160316/?merchant=Plantstraws">plant straws</a> are effective and lovely to behold. The metal straws are available in many colors, including solid brass, but you must supply your <a href="https://plantstraws.co/products/pipe-vase" rel="noopener" target="_blank">own water container</a>. Our only gripe is the cost of shipping, which turned a $50 pack of two straws into $65.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><div class="ff31b4af" data-ad-element="outer_ad_container" data-scp="removed"><div class="e5d43c70"><p class="cca4d3b6">Advertisement</p><a href="#after-dfp-ad-chapter-mid-9" class="css-777zgl">SKIP ADVERTISEMENT</a><div class="ad dfp-ad-chapter-mid-9-wrapper css-rfqw0c" id="dfp-ad-chapter-mid-9"></div><div id="after-dfp-ad-chapter-mid-9"></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></section><section class="b6d81848 d47f7b03" id="monthly-tea-towels" expanded=""><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0 e5f9b502"><h2 class="e823fba7" aria-controls="monthly-tea-towels-panel" aria-selected