ton"><span>$20</span> from <span>Gingiber</span></a></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>For about $16 per month, this small, woman-owned business in Arkansas will send a newly designed <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/55255/189351/4/160318/?merchant=Gingiber" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Gingiber" data-pick-type-id="7" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/55255/189351/4/160318/?merchant=Gingiber" data-vars-store="Gingiber" data-gtm-context="chapter_monthly-tea-towels" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Gingiber" data-pid="55255" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/55255/189351/4/160318/?merchant=Gingiber">100% cotton flour-sack tea towel</a> to your mother-in-law every 30 days. Artist Stacie Bloomfield bedecks the towels with bright colors and flora- and fauna-inspired screen prints, and the fabric is soft and absorbent. After you subscribe, your MIL will receive her first towel within seven days, and then an exclusive towel will arrive once a month until you cancel. All taxes and shipping are included in the price, and she can pause delivery temporarily if needed. If $16 for a dishrag seems steep, think of them as paper towel replacements—and take a peek on the company website for the pages and pages of thrilled recipients.</p></div></div></div></div></div></section><section class="b6d81848 d47f7b03" id="bird-watching-station" expanded=""><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0 e5f9b502"><h2 class="e823fba7" aria-controls="bird-watching-station-panel" aria-selected="true" role="tab" tabindex="0" data-gtm-element="chapter_heading" data-gtm-trigger="single_chapter" data-chapter-name="Bird-watching station" data-expand-close="close" data-chapter-index="16">Bird-watching station</h2></div></div><div id="bird-watching-station-panel" class="fa265be5" aria-labelledby="bird-watching-station" aria-hidden="false" role="tabpanel"><div class=" chapter__content-wrapper"><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><figure id="attachment_365140" class="wp-caption alignnone"><div class="ec5f8867 global_chapter__arp_image" style="padding-bottom:66.70%;display:inline"><img alt="An acrylic bird feeder with colorful birds and birdseed shot against a green backdrop." data-src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/05/giftsformotherinlaw-2048px-07085.jpg?auto=webp&amp;width=1024" width="1024" height="683" class="cf3feb4c c882c9ce alignnone size-large wp-image-365140" loading="lazy"/></div><figcaption class="wp-caption-text"> <!-- --> <span class="wp-caption-text wp-caption-credit">Photo: Marki Williams</span></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><div class="ebb615ab global-cob e1e566ad" data-scp="callout"><div id="callout-chapter-2-29" class="fd1ac384" data-scp="callout_item" data-testid="callout" data-pid="55235"><span class="ddf294c5"><div class="fabe3ad3"><div class="e14704b2" role="button" tabindex="0" data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="55235"><span aria-label="Save Product" class="a478f5d2  " data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="55235"></span></div></div></span><div class="f1cabe17"><div class="f31f6df1"><div class="efc734d0 eae76d54"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/55235/189299/4/176790?merchant=Amazon" class="fa8c1483 product-merchant-link-button" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/55235/189299/4/176790?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_image" data-scp="removed" tabindex="-1" data-pid="55235" data-gtm-context="inline"><div class="ec5f8867 global_chapter__arp_image"><img alt="" itemProp="image" data-src="https://d1b5h9psu9yexj.cloudfront.net/55235/Jarkyfine-Window-Bird-Feeder_20230412-195951_full.jpeg" width="570" height="380" class="cf3feb4c c882c9ce" loading="lazy"/></div></a></div><div class="ce2bb787"><div><h3 class="b550f131 e26624a1 a1a87f29"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/55235/189299/4/176790?merchant=Amazon" class="dfb6b88d" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" title="Jarkyfine Window Bird Feeder" data-gtm-element="callout_product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="2" data-pid="55235" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/55235/189299/4/176790?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_name" data-scp="callout_product" data-gtm-context="inline">Jarkyfine Window Bird Feeder</a></h3><h2 class="eafb159a"></h2></div><p class="ec57f3ca" data-scp="callout_description">Strong suction cups and a roomy acrylic structure readily accommodate multiple avian visitors. It’s squirrel-proof, and it can get messy, but it’s easy to clean.</p><div class="dded66b7"><div data-scp="removed"><h4 class="efa3259d">Buying Options</h4><div class="b279b202 product-pricebox-0" data-source-id-order="0" data-country-code="US"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/55235/189299/4/176790?merchant=Amazon" class="b50e01ee" data-gtm-element="callout_buy_button_impression" data-link-type="button" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="2" data-pid="55235" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/55235/189299/4/176790?merchant=Amazon" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-gtm-context="inline" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_button"><span>$30</span> from <span>Amazon</span></a></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>We’re convinced that it’s good for your health to watch birds flit about while you’re drinking your morning coffee, washing the dishes, or listening to a podcast. This <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/55235/189299/4/176789/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="2" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/55235/189299/4/176789/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_bird-watching-station" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="55235" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/55235/189299/4/176789/?merchant=Amazon">acrylic feeding house</a> secures to the outside of a window, and it holds up to 12 pounds of birds and seeds, thanks to four suction cups that really stay put. And because squirrels can’t climb glass, you don’t have to worry about them stealing food. Like all feeders, this one does get messy after a while. Happily, the segmented seed tray slides out for easy filling and soap-and-water cleaning.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><div class="ff31b4af" data-ad-element="outer_ad_container" data-scp="removed"><div class="e5d43c70"><p class="cca4d3b6">Advertisement</p><a href="#after-dfp-ad-chapter-mid-10" class="css-777zgl">SKIP ADVERTISEMENT</a><div class="ad dfp-ad-chapter-mid-10-wrapper css-rfqw0c" id="dfp-ad-chapter-mid-10"></div><div id="after-dfp-ad-chapter-mid-10"></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></section><section class="b6d81848 d47f7b03" id="a-perfect-box-of-chocolates" expanded=""><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0 e5f9b502"><h2 class="e823fba7" aria-controls="a-perfect-box-of-chocolates-pan