 data-gtm-context="inline" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_button"><span>$52</span> from <span>Recchiuti Confections</span><br/><span>(16 pieces)</span></a></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>If your MIL is a chocoholic, you can’t go wrong with these <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/12847/36685/4/160320/?merchant=Recchiuti%20Confections" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Recchiuti Confections" data-pick-type-id="7" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/12847/36685/4/160320/?merchant=Recchiuti%20Confections" data-vars-store="Recchiuti Confections" data-gtm-context="chapter_a-perfect-box-of-chocolates" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Recchiuti Confections" data-pid="12847" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/12847/36685/4/160320/?merchant=Recchiuti%20Confections">fancy chocolates</a> (from San Francisco), which are some of our <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/gifts/best-boxed-chocolates/">favorite boxed chocolates</a>. The price is definitely eyebrow-raising for 16 chocolates, but it’s justifiable if you think of each piece as an epicurean treasure. Recchiuti Confections specializes in classic flavors like Caramel and Hazelnut, and it ventures off the beaten path with Tarragon Grapefruit or Star Anise and Pink Peppercorn. No matter how unusual the flavors, they never overpower the taste of the chocolate itself. Editor-in-chief Ben Frumin says that when he ordered a box for his wife, “She declared them unequivocally the best and most stylish chocolates she’d ever had.”</p></div></div></div></div></div></section><section class="b6d81848 d47f7b03" id="bracelets-with-meaning" expanded=""><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0 e5f9b502"><h2 class="e8